# 2. Secured and monitored web infrastructure

Whiteboard design of a three-server web infrastructure hosting
`www.foobar.com` that is **secured** (firewalls), **encrypted** (HTTPS via an
SSL certificate), and **monitored** (monitoring clients on every server).

## Diagram

```
                              ( User )
                                  |
                  https://www.foobar.com (encrypted, port 443)
                                  |
                          HTTPS over TCP/IP
                                  |
                       [ Firewall #1 ]
                                  |
                                  v
                  +-------------------------------+
                  |   Load Balancer (HAProxy)     |
                  |   SSL certificate / HTTPS     |
                  |   Round Robin                 |
                  |   + monitoring client         |
                  +---------------+---------------+
                       /                     \
              [ Firewall #2 ]          [ Firewall #3 ]
                    /                          \
                   v                            v
        +-----------------------+   +-----------------------+
        |       Server 1        |   |       Server 2        |
        |  Nginx (web)          |   |  Nginx (web)          |
        |  Application server   |   |  Application server   |
        |  App files (code)     |   |  App files (code)     |
        |  MySQL (Primary)      |   |  MySQL (Replica)      |
        |  Monitoring client    |   |  Monitoring client    |
        +-----------------------+   +-----------------------+
                                  |
                                  v
                    +-----------------------------+
                    |  Monitoring service          |
                    |  (Sumologic / collector SaaS)|
                    +-----------------------------+
```

## Why each additional element is added

- **3 firewalls:** one in front of the load balancer and one in front of each
  server, to filter network traffic and only allow the connections that are
  supposed to happen (e.g. HTTPS in, app/DB ports only between the right
  hosts). They reduce the attack surface and block unauthorized access.
- **SSL certificate (HTTPS):** so `www.foobar.com` is served over HTTPS and
  traffic between users and the infrastructure is encrypted, protecting data
  from eavesdropping and tampering.
- **3 monitoring clients:** one data-collector agent per server (LB + 2
  servers) to gather metrics and logs and send them to the monitoring service,
  giving visibility into health, performance, and security.

## Specifics to explain

### What are firewalls for?
A firewall is a network security system that controls incoming and outgoing
traffic based on a set of rules. It allows legitimate traffic and blocks
everything else, protecting servers from unauthorized access and attacks.

### Why is the traffic served over HTTPS?
HTTPS encrypts the traffic between the user's browser and the website using
SSL/TLS. This keeps data (passwords, cookies, personal information)
confidential and tamper-proof in transit, and prevents man-in-the-middle
attacks. Without it, anyone on the network path could read or alter the data.

### What is monitoring used for?
Monitoring is used to observe the health and behavior of the infrastructure:
performance metrics (CPU, memory, response time), traffic, errors, downtime,
and security events. It lets you detect problems early, alert on incidents,
diagnose issues, and plan capacity.

### How is the monitoring tool collecting data?
A **monitoring client (agent)** is installed on each server. It collects local
metrics and reads log files, then pushes that data to the central monitoring
service (e.g. Sumologic) over the network. The service aggregates the data and
presents dashboards and alerts.

### How to monitor your web server QPS
QPS = Queries Per Second. To monitor it, configure the web server (Nginx) to
log every request, and have the monitoring agent parse/count those access-log
entries over time. Create a metric/query in the monitoring tool that counts
requests per second (e.g. count of log lines per second), then build a
dashboard panel and alerts on it. (Alternatively, expose Nginx's
`stub_status`/metrics endpoint and have the agent scrape the request counter.)

## Issues with this infrastructure

### Why is terminating SSL at the load balancer level an issue?
If SSL is **terminated** at the load balancer, traffic is decrypted there and
then travels **unencrypted** from the load balancer to the backend servers
(inside the infrastructure). Anyone able to observe that internal traffic can
read it in clear text, so the data is not protected end-to-end.

### Why is having only one MySQL server able to accept writes an issue?
Only the **Primary** accepts writes, so it is a **single point of failure for
writes**: if it goes down, the application can no longer write data (only read
from replicas) until a replica is promoted. It is also a write bottleneck that
cannot be scaled horizontally for writes.

### Why might having servers with all the same components be a problem?
Each server runs the **web server, application server, and database** together.
This means components compete for the same resources (CPU, RAM, disk, network),
making it hard to scale or tune any single component independently. It also
increases the attack surface per server and complicates maintenance, since
everything is coupled on the same machine.
